1216 To be expended for the Bullying Prevention Project in accordance with Title
1217 16, Chapter 28B, Code of Alabama 1975. The State Superintendent of Education
1218 shall distribute the above appropriation as grants to local education
1219 agencies. These agencies may be awarded funds only after application to the
1220 State Department of Education. The grant application process may require the
1221 submission of plans by the applicant to meet the requirements set forth in
1222 Chapter 28B of Title 16. In the awarding of grants, preference will be given
1223 to applicants seeking to develop and implement evidence-based practices to
1224 promote a school environment that is free of harassment, intimidation,
1225 violence, and threats of violence. This program may also address tier one
1226 and tier two of the school-based mental health model of all students
1227 receiving prevention education and peers working to support and identify
1228 at-risk students. Additionally, the program may focus to increase school
1229 safety through early identification of at-risk students, minimizing
1230 disciplinary infractions including school suspensions and expulsions. The
1231 program may provide grade level prevention curriculum for all students and,
1232 in that case, the curriculum must be updated annually to remain current and
1233 relevant to current trends that youth face in their lives. Any applicable
1234 prevention curriculum must be comprehensive and satisfy the following state
1235 mandates: Erin's Law, Jamari Terrell Williams Student Bullying Prevention
1236 Act, Jason Flatt Act, Price Hornsby Act, and drugs and alcohol prevention
1237 programs. In addition, any program related to mental health should be
1238 flexible enough to focus on the greatest mental health needs for each
1239 individual school. For accountability purposes, reporting data must include
1240 the number of students engaged in the programs, the number of students
1241 supported, and the number of students referred to adults as at-risk.
