1276 This appropriation shall be used for the State Department of Education, in
1277 consultation with the Department of Early Childhood Education, to fund a
1278 program to be known as the Governor's Turnaround Schools. These grants are
1279 for the lowest performing public elementary schools which are identified as
1280 underperforming by the State Superintendent in consideration of the
1281 provisions of the Alabama Accountability Act, the State Report Card System,
1282 and other criteria as determined by the State Superintendent. The intent of
1283 these grants is to identify and target specific deficiencies of each
1284 individual underperforming elementary school and target said deficiencies
1285 with high quality and innovative educational supports. In consultation with
1286 these schools as well as the local education agencies that respectively
1287 oversee these schools, the State Department of Education will develop and
1288 oversee a comprehensive plan for school improvement. It is the intention of
1289 this provision that all areas of the State Department, including Alabama
1290 Reading Initiative, Alabama Math, Science, and Technology Initiative, Office
1291 of Mathematics Improvement, and Office of School Improvement, will work
1292 together to best serve these selected schools. Schools previously named to
1293 this list will be known as Cohort 1. Beginning with the fiscal year 2027
1294 Budget Request, the State Department will recommend a pathway for schools in
1295 Cohort 1 to exit this program, and the Department will recommend new schools
1296 to replace those exiting the program in subsequent years. These schools may
1297 be known as Cohort 2 and so forth. The State Superintendent may also request
1298 additional funds so that additional cohorts can be expanded as Cohort 1
1299 schools leave the program over the next few years. Any expansion of new
1300 Cohorts should be modest with respect to the purpose of this program which
1301 is expected to offer extraordinary supports to a relatively limited number
1302 of schools at a time. The State Department of Education should annually
1303 produce written progress reports on these schools to the Chair of the House
1304 Ways and Means - Education Committee, the Chair of the Senate Finance and
1305 Taxation - Education Committee, the Governor, and the Local School Board,
